revision.text:
'''Broken-Backed War Theory''' is a form of conflict that could transpire after a [[Nuclear warfare|massive nuclear exchange]]. Assuming that following a nuclear exchange all the participants have not been utterly annihilated, there may arise a scenario unique to military strategy and theory, one in which all or some of the parties involved strive to continue fighting until the other side is decisively defeated.
{{War}}
== Origin of the phrase == Broken-Backed War Theory was first formally elaborated on in the 1952 British ''[[White Paper|Defence White Paper]]'', to describe what would presumably happen after a [[Nuclear warfare|major nuclear exchange]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Redford|first1=Duncan|last2=Grove|first2=Philip|title=The Royal Navy: A History Since 1900 (A History of the Royal Navy)|date=29 May 2014|publisher=I. B. Tauris|isbn=978-1780767826|page=230}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=p6p_O-iTSm4C&pg=PA269&lpg=PA269&ots=P7YE6SXN23&focus=viewport&dq=broken+backed+war&output=html_text|title = Arms, Economics and British Strategy: From Dreadnoughts to Hydrogen Bombs|last = Peden|first = G. C.|date = 2007-02-08|publisher = Cambridge University Press|isbn = 9781139462921|language = en}}</ref> The American "New Look Strategy of 1953/54" utterly rejected the notion of Broken-Backed war. They dropped the term from the 1955 white paper, and the phrase has since faded from common usage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zellen|first1=Barry Scott|title=State of Doom: Bernard Brodie, The Bomb, and the Birth of the Bipolar World|date=December 2011|publisher=Continuum|isbn=9781441161345|page=109}}</ref>
== Commentary == Klaus Knorr purported, that in a broken-backed war scenario, only military weapons and vehicles on hand prior to the sustained hostilities would be of use, as the economic potential of both sides would be, at least in theory, utterly shattered. {{cquote| Do current predictions on the nature of future warfare exhaust not only all possible, but all likely, contingencies? It can be granted that a long-drawn-out and massive war conducted with conventional, by which I mean modernized but nonatomic, weapons, is so unlikely to occur that it may be safely neglected as a contingency. There definitely is no future for World War II. It can also be granted that, once unlimited thermonuclear war has broken out, there is no economic war potential to be mobilized for its conduct.''' Even a broken-backed war would have to be fought overwhelmingly, if not entirely, with munitions on hand at the start of the fighting.''' ~ '''Klaus Knorr'''<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/2009224?sid=21105415387731&uid=3739704&uid=4&uid=3739256&uid=2][https://digitalndulibrary.ndu.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=%2Ficafarchive&CISOPTR=39960&REC=4&CISOBOX=broken+backed Klaus E. Knorr, The Concept of Economic Potential for War, 1957] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222045521/https://digitalndulibrary.ndu.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=%2Ficafarchive&CISOPTR=39960&REC=4&CISOBOX=broken+backed |date=February 22, 2015 }}</ref>}}
[[Herman Kahn]] in his tome [[On Thermonuclear War]], has posited that a broken-backed war is implausible, because one side would likely absorb vastly more damage than its opposition. As he was writing in the late 1950s, when the nuclear arsenals of the [[Nuclear weapons and the Soviet Union|Soviet Union]] and the [[Nuclear weapons of the United States|United States]] numbered in the tens of thousands, the validity of this statement in the modern war can be called into question. {{cquote|The "broken-back" war notion is obsolete not only because of the possibility of mutual devastation but even more because it is so very unlikely that the forces of both sides would become attrited in even roughly the same way. One side is likely to get a rather commanding advantage and exploit this lead to force the other side to choose between surrender and the physical destruction of its capability to continue. '''Herman Kahn'''}} <ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EN2gtPTjFd8C|title = On Thermonuclear War|last = Kahn|first = Herman|date = 2011-12-31|publisher = Transaction Publishers|isbn = 9781412815598|language = en}}</ref>
The nuclear strategist [[Bernard Brodie (military strategist)|Bernard Brodie]] argued that this form of conflict may be impractical simply because it is almost impossible to plan for. His writings on the subject came before the advent of [[counterforce|Counter-force]] doctrine, and during a time of nuclear plenty, when it was safe to assume that a nuclear exchange would render a nation's industry useless.<ref>[http://www.rand.org/pubs/commercial_books/CB137-1.html Bernard Brodie, Strategy in the Missile Age]</ref><ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/606443.pdf IMPLICATIONS OF NUCLEAR WEAPONS IN TOTAL WAR; Bernard Brodie, 1957]</ref><ref>[http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/605006.pdf Nuclear Weapons and Changing Strategic Outlooks; Bernard Brodie, 1956]</ref>
During the [[Cold War]], Colonel Virgil Ney hypothesized that a nuclear exchange alone would not be enough to defeat the Soviet Union, and he argued for a modest construction of underground facilities and infrastructure.<ref>{{Cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nHFCKmo2PH8C|title = One Nation Underground: The Fallout Shelter in American Culture|last = Rose|first = Kenneth D.|date = 2004-05-01|publisher = NYU Press|isbn = 9780814775233|language = en}}</ref>
==In popular culture== In the novel, ''[[Final Blackout]]'' by [[L. Ron Hubbard]], the conflict between the survivors of London and the United States has been characterized as a Broken-Backed War by some critics.{{cn|date=January 2018}}
The table-top [[Role-playing game]] [[Twilight 2000]] released by [[Game Designers' Workshop]] in 1984 entails a Broken-Backed War; in the aftermath of a nuclear exchange in 1997, by 2000, [[Warsaw Pact]] and [[NATO]] forces are still fighting for a decisive victory in Europe and elsewhere with dwindling conventional arms and munitions.{{cn|date=January 2018}}
