{{Infobox power station | name = Copiapó Solar Project | name_official = Proyecto Copiapó Solar | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Chile | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | location_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|27|21|S|70|19|W|region:CL_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = [[Chile]] | location = [[Copiapó]], [[Atacama Region|Atacama]] | status = P | construction_began = | commissioned = 2019 (planned) | decommissioned = | cost = $2 billion | owner = Copiapó Energía Solar SpA | operator = <!------------------------- SOLAR FARMS --> | solar_type = CSP | solar_concentration = | solar_csp_technology = T | solar_csp_collectors = | solar_field_aperture = | solar_cpvt = | solar_site_area = | solar_resource = <!------------------------- GENERAL --> | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = 2 x 120 [[megawatt|MW]], 1 x 150 [[megawatt|MW]] (PV) | ps_units_decommissioned = | ps_storage_hours = 14 hours | ps_electrical_capacity = 260 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = 74.6% (planned) | ps_annual_generation = 1,700 [[GWh]] | website = {{URL|http://www.solarreserve.com/}} | extra = Priced at [[Penny (United States coin)|¢]]6.3/kWh ($63/MWh)<ref name=Kraemer >{{cite web|url= https://cleantechnica.com/2017/03/13/solarreserve-bids-24-hour-solar-6-3-cents-chile/ |title=SolarReserve Bids 24-Hour Solar At 6.3 Cents In Chile |first=Susan |last=Kraemer |publisher=CleanTechnica |date=13 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> }}
The '''Copiapó Solar Project''' is a 260&nbsp;[[megawatt]] (MW) net [[solar thermal power]] project to be located near [[Copiapó]], about 65 kilometers east of the coastal [[List of towns in Chile|town]] of [[Caldera, Chile|Caldera]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/solarreserve-obtiene-aprobacion-ambiental-para-construir-una-central-de-concentracion-solar-de-260-mw-522386791.html |title=Solarreserve Obtiene Aprobación Ambiental para Construir una Central de Concentración Solar de 260 MW |date=August 20, 2015 |publisher=PR Newswire Association LLC |accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> The project is being developed by [[SolarReserve]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solarreserve.com/en/newsroom/press-releases/solarreserve-receives-environmental-approval-for-260-megawatt-baseload-solar-plant-in-chile/@@download/file/SOLARRESERVE%20RECEIVES%20ENVIRONMENTAL%20APPROVAL%20FOR%20260%20MEGAWATT%20BASELOAD%20SOLAR%20PLANT%20IN%20CHILE.pdf |title=SolarReserve Receives Environmental Approval for 260 Megawatt Baseload Solar Plant in Chile |publisher=SolarReserve, LLC |accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> and is scheduled to reach commercial operation in 2019.
The Copiapó project will comprise two 120 megawatt ([[megawatt|MW]], 130 [[megawatt|MW]] gross) solar thermal towers with up to 14 hours thermal storage, combined with 150 [[megawatt|MW]] of [[Photovoltaics|PV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solarreserve.com/en/global-projects/csp/copiapo |title=Copiapó, Atacama Region, Chile |publisher=SolarReserve, LLC |accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> The hybrid project will deliver over 1,700 gigawatt hours ([[gigawatt hour|GW·h]]) annually, as non-intermittent baseload power, 24 hours a day. The project uses [[heliostat]] mirrors that collect and focus the sun's thermal energy to heat [[molten salt]] flowing through a [[solar power tower]]. The molten salt circulates from the tower to a storage tank, where it is then used to produce steam and generate electricity. Excess thermal energy is stored in the molten salt and can be used to generate power for up to fourteen hours, including during the evening hours and when direct sunlight is not available. The project's solar tower component technology is based on the SolarReserve [[Crescent Dunes Solar Energy Project]] in the US.
The project is expected to cost $2 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powerengineeringint.com/articles/2015/08/chile-approves-260-mw-solar-power-plant.html |title=Chile approves 260 MW solar power plant |date=August 24, 2015 |publisher=Power Engineering International |accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref>
The Copiapó Solar project was submitted to a full environmental assessment under the Chilean system of Environmental Impact Assessment (SEIA) administered by the Department of Environmental Assessment (SEA), and received an Environmental Qualification Resolution (RCA), as it is called the Chilean environmental permit, on August 19, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sea.gob.cl/agenda/tabla-de-comision-de-evaluacion-region-de-atacama-9 |title=Tabla Sesión Ordinaria N° 12/2015 Comisión de Evaluación de Atacama |publisher=Servicio de Evaluación Ambiental |accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref>
The hybrid concept combines two or more energy conversion mechanisms, that when integrated, overcome limitations inherent in either. The purpose is to provide a high level of energy security and reliability through the integrated mix of complementary generation methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cleantechnica.com/2015/04/02/csp-pv-hybrid-plants-gain-sway-chile/ |title=CSP & PV Hybrid Plants Gain Sway In Chile |date=April 2, 2015 |publisher=CleanTechnica, Sustainable Enterprises Media, Inc. |accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://social.csptoday.com/markets/chile-sun-mine-about-be-exploited |title=Chile: a sun mine about to be exploited |date=October 10, 2014 |publisher= CSP Today, FC Business Intelligence Limited |accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> Specifically, photovoltaics, to date, has a lower cost if one ignores the [[Dispatchable generation|dispatchability]] question, that instead is solved by the solar thermal component.
At the 2017-01 auction, SolarReserve bid $63/MWh for 24-hour CSP power with no subsidies, competing with other types such as LNG gas turbines.<ref name=Kraemer /> And in the following auction they bid less than 5 ¢/kWh.<ref>[http://www.solarpaces.org/solarreserve-bids-csp-5-cents-chilean-auction/ SolarReserve Bids CSP Under 5 Cents in Chilean Auction], Soalr Paces October 29, 2017 "SolarReserve Bids CSP Under 5 Cents in Chilean Auction".</ref> ==See also== {{stack|{{Portal|Chile|Sustainable development|Renewable energy}}}} {{Div col|colwidth=28em}} * [[Atacama region|Atacama]] * [[Atacama Desert]] * [[List of solar thermal power stations]] * [[Solar power in Chile]] * [[Solar thermal energy]] {{Div col end}}
