{{other uses|indigenous (disambiguation){{!}}indigenous}}
{{For|humans|Indigenous peoples}}
{{dictionary}}

In [[biogeography]], a [[species]] is '''indigenous''' to a given region or [[ecosystem]] if its presence in that region is the result of only natural processes, with no human intervention.<ref name="CEQ2">CEQ (1999). [https://web.archive.org/web/20080515154626/http://ceq.eh.doe.gov/nepa/regs/eos/eo13112.html Executive Order 13112] </ref> The term is equivalent to ''native'' in less scientific usage. Every wild organism (as opposed to a [[domestication|domesticated]] organism) has its own natural range of distribution in which it is regarded as indigenous. Outside this native range, a species may be introduced by human activity, either intentionally or unintentionally; it is then referred to as an ''[[introduced species]]'' within the regions where it was [[Human impact on the environment#anthropogenic |anthropogenically]] introduced.<ref name="IntroducedDS">{{cite web|title=Introduced species|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/terms/introduced_species.htm|website=Science Daily|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>

The notion of 'indigenous' is of necessity a blurred concept, and is clearly a function of both time and political boundaries. Seen over long periods of time, plants take part in the constant movement of tectonic plates - species appear and may flourish, endure or become extinct, but their distribution is never static or confined to a particular geographic location.

An indigenous species is not necessarily [[endemism|endemic]]. In biology and ecology, endemic means ''exclusively'' native to the [[biota (ecology)|biota]] of a specific place. An indigenous species may occur in areas other than the one under consideration.

The terms ''endemic'' and ''indigenous'' do not imply that an organism necessarily originated or [[evolution|evolved]] from where it is found.

