 Reventazon River |url= http://www.gettyimages.at/detail/nachrichtenfoto/view-of-the-hydroelectric-dam-on-the-reventazon-river-nachrichtenfoto/606993636?#view-of-the-hydroelectric-dam-on-the-reventazon-river-in-siquirres-in-picture-id606993636 |publisher= Ezequiel Becerra |agency=AFP |accessdate= 17 September 2016}}</ref> and its primary purpose is the production of [[hydroelectric]] power. The 1.4 billion USD project and largest power station in the country has an installed capacity of 305.5 MW and is expected to provide power for 525,000 homes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Costa Rica's president inaugurates Central America's largest hydropower plant |url= http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2016-09/17/content_39313337.htm |publisher= China.org.cn |accessdate= 17 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Reventazón Hydropower Project |url= http://idbdocs.iadb.org/wsdocs/getdocument.aspx?docnum=36879354 |publisher= Inter-America Development Bank |accessdate= 20 December 2014 |date= 22 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Reventazón - A new butterfly valve for the penstock of the largest hydropower project in Costa Rica |url= http://www.andritz.com/hydro/hydronews/hy-hydro-news-26/hy-26-21-reventazon.htm |publisher= Andritz |accessdate= 20 December 2014}}</ref> Construction on the dam began in 2009. At a height of {{Convert|130|m|ft}} and with a structural volume of {{Convert|9,000,000|m3|cuyd|abbr=on}}, it is the largest dam in [[Central America]]. To produce electricity, water from the reservoir is diverted about {{cvt|3|km}} to the northeast where it reaches the power station along the Reventazón River.<ref>{{cite web |title= Project of the Month |url= http://www.pedregal.co.cr/pgproyectomes.htm |publisher= Pedregal |accessdate= 20 December 2014 |language= Spanish}}</ref> Due to its environmental features, like offset habitats and migration corridors for jaguars and many other species, the project could be a model for other future hydroelectric power plants.<ref>{{cite report |authors= Joerg Hartmann, David Harrison, Je Opperman, and Roger Gill |date= 18 November 2013 |title= The Next Frontier of Hydropower Sustainability: Planning at the System Scale |url= https://publications.iadb.org/bitstream/handle/11319/6505/The%20Next%20Frontier%20of%20Hydropower%20Sustainability%20-%20Planning%20at%20the%20System%20Scale.pdf?sequence=1 |at= 16pp. |access-date= 17 September 2016 |quote= }}</ref>
