{{Infobox Russian city |en_name = Rudnaya Pristan |ru_name = Рудная Пристань |image_skyline = |image_caption = |coordinates = {{coord|44|21|31|N|135|48|37|E|display=inline,title}} |map_label_position = right |image_coa = |coa_caption = |holiday = |federal_subject = [[Primorsky Krai]] |adm_data_as_of = |adm_city_jur = |adm_ctr_of = |inhabloc_cat = Village |mun_data_as_of = |urban_okrug_jur = |mun_admctr_of = |leader_title = |leader_name = |representative_body= |area_km2 = |pop_2010census = 2107 |pop_2010census_ref = <ref name="2010Census">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref> |pop_density = |pop_density_as_of = |established_date = official 1910 (settlement began 1866) |postal_codes = 692434 |dialing_codes = |website = |date = May 2010 }} '''Rudnaya Pristan''' ({{lang-ru|Ру́дная При́стань}}, lit. ''[[Ore]] [[Wharf]]'') is a [[types of settlements in Russia|village]] (''[[village#Russia|selo]]'') located at the mouth of the [[Rudnaya River]], on the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] coast of [[Primorsky Krai]]. It is situated 35&nbsp;km east of [[Dalnegorsk]] (also in [[Primorsky Krai]]) and approximately 514&nbsp;km north of [[Vladivostok]]. Its population was 2,107 in 2010, 2,389 in 2002,<ref>([[Russian Census (2002)|2002 Census]])</ref> and 2,947 in 1989.<ref>([[Soviet Census (1989)|1989 Census]]).</ref>
[[Lead]] [[smelting]] has been the town's primary industry since a plant was built there in 1930. The plant has provided steady employment for most of the area's families since that time, but at enormous cost to both the health of the residents and the local environment. The residents suffer from many health problems, including an inordinately high rate of [[cancer]], and the soil has become heavily contaminated with lead-related by-products. The [[Blacksmith Institute]] consequently declared Rudnaya Pristan, along with [[Dalnegorsk]], one of the ten worst polluted places on earth,<ref>[http://www.blacksmithinstitute.org/site10j.php Website of Blacksmith Institute]</ref> although [[Anatoly Lebedev]], leader of the ecological [[non-governmental organization|NGO]] ''BROK'', disputes this inclusion.<ref>Regnum New Agency. ''[http://www.regnum.ru/english/725071.html Ecologists of Primorye Territory (Russia) surprised at listing Rudnaya Pristan among the most polluted places in the world]''</ref>
Despite its coastal location, Rudnaya Pristan's harbor has remained largely undeveloped, and its [[climate]] is harsh, dominated in winter by the vast Siberian high-pressure system and in summer by remnants of the East Asian [[monsoon]]. This combination results in very cold, dry winters with generally high winds, and muggy summers that provide ideal conditions for the breeding of [[mosquito]]es.
